# architecture-metaclass-threadlocal-thread-safety — History

## v1.2.0 (2026-07-05)

**Changed by:** ProjectHephaestus issue #1858 — SECOND, sharper planning iteration.
The R0 plan (captured in v1.1.0 as the "Proposed Workflow" + its five risks) was graded
**F / NOGO** and RE-PLANNED to GO. This entry records how the R1 re-plan RESOLVED the R0
risks with ground-truth evidence rather than merely re-flagging them (still plan-only —
no code applied, no tests run, CI not confirmed).
**Verification:** unverified (planning session; the R1 resolutions cite source `file:line`
read this session, but no code was applied and CI was not run)

### What changed

- Promoted the shared-cache section from a bare risk register to a **resolved R1 design**:
  each of the R0 risks that v1.1.0 left as "verify whether…" is now converted into a
  DECISION backed by a grep/read result, per the "resolve the reviewer's deepest risk,
  don't re-flag it" rule.
  - **Risk 1 (per-repo key may be a no-op under shared CWD) RESOLVED.**
    `grep -n chdir hephaestus/automation/pipeline/**` → ZERO hits; every subprocess is
    launched with an explicit `cwd=` (`worker_pool.py:246,303,419,451`; stages pass
    `cwd=_worktree_path(item, ctx)`). Decision: a CWD-derived key WOULD collide across
    threads, so the pipeline's real isolation is (a) the org-path `refresh=True` +
    (b) the lock — the key is NOT load-bearing under shared CWD; it stays meaningful only
    because legacy callers are single-repo-per-process.
  - **Risk 4 (resolver attribute shape unverified) RESOLVED.** Ground truth
    `git_utils.py:76`: `get_repo_info(repo_root: Path | None = None) -> tuple[str, str]`
    returning `(owner, repo_name)` — a TUPLE, not an object with `.owner`/`.name`. It is
    memoized per resolved root (`_repo_info_cache.get_or_compute`, `git_utils.py:124`) and
    accepts an explicit `repo_root`, so it need not read CWD and per-call cost is a dict
    lookup after warmup. The R0 `getattr(info, "owner")` slug was WRONG; use tuple unpack
    `owner, name = get_repo_info(repo_root)`.
- Added the **"don't over-scope the fix to callers that were never broken"** lesson:
  `gh_list_labels`/`gh_create_label` have many single-repo-per-process legacy callers
  (loop_runner, pr_manager, _review_phase, implementer_phase_runner, planner_review_loop)
  that were fine with the un-keyed cache; the multi-repo hazard is ONLY the pipeline
  coordinator. Minimal correct fix = repo-keyed dict + lock + defensive copy (backward
  compatible) AND the structural org-path `refresh=True` — do NOT churn the safe callers
  onto a new API.
- Corrected the misleading GIL aside into a hardened contract: `entry.add()` and
  get-then-set are read-modify-write and NOT atomic; the lock is load-bearing. Added the
  `test_returned_set_is_a_defensive_copy` contract and made create's add atomic-under-lock.
- Bumped `version` 1.1.0 → 1.2.0 (minor — resolves prior risks with evidence, adds the
  over-scope lesson and defensive-copy contract; no rewrite of the verified pattern (A)).
  `date` stays 2026-07-05; `verification` stays `unverified` (newest material plan-only).

### Why

v1.1.0 shipped the #1858 fix as a design + a five-item risk register. That register was the
R0 plan, and it was graded **F / NOGO** — a re-plan was required. The durable lesson (also
cross-linked from the new `tooling-plan-artifact-delivery-nogo` skill and the
`architecture-executable-convention-guard-pattern` NOGO→GO sub-pattern) is that a re-plan
which merely REPEATS the reviewer's open questions ("verify whether…") re-earns the NOGO.
The R1 pass RESOLVED them: it ran the `chdir` grep, read `get_repo_info`'s actual signature,
and converted each risk into a design decision the implementer can act on without
re-deriving. Capturing the resolved form (not just the questions) is what makes the skill
actionable on the next shared-cache retrofit.

